00:13:58,628 --> 00:14:00,069
So what's the player fantasy?

239
00:14:00,129 --> 00:14:01,671
If the fantasy and the goals aren't there,

240
00:14:01,691 --> 00:14:02,952
it's probably a bad idea.

241
00:14:04,053 --> 00:14:07,055
In Deus Ex it was, you're a James Bond figure,

242
00:14:07,335 --> 00:14:08,396
at least this is where we started,

243
00:14:08,937 --> 00:14:10,078
who's equally good at fighting,

244
00:14:10,098 --> 00:14:11,619
sneaking and charming people,

245
00:14:11,759 --> 00:14:13,660
which is a pretty solid fantasy.

246
00:14:14,804 --> 00:14:21,791
What does the player do? What are the verbs of the game? Games are about doing, like I said. At

247
00:14:21,831 --> 00:14:28,278
some level, if you boil it down, it's about running, jumping, sneaking, talking, fighting,

248
00:14:28,398 --> 00:14:33,463
you know, which are all good, solid game verbs. There was nothing innovative about the verbs of

249
00:14:33,483 --> 00:14:37,347
the game. They were just good, solid game verbs. And then we get to the 2 plus 1.

250
00:14:39,459 --> 00:14:40,920
Has anyone done this before?

251
00:14:41,380 --> 00:14:41,761
Okay.

252
00:14:42,341 --> 00:14:44,642
If someone has done it before, what can we learn from them?

253
00:14:45,243 --> 00:14:47,844
And if no one's done it before, what does that tell us?

254
00:14:47,904 --> 00:14:49,445
It could be a really bad idea.

255
00:14:50,206 --> 00:14:51,266
Okay.

256
00:14:51,527 --> 00:14:53,468
Or it could be so original that it's something

257
00:14:53,508 --> 00:14:55,169
that could change the world of gaming.

258
00:14:55,209 --> 00:14:56,049
You know, you just don't know,

259
00:14:56,089 --> 00:14:57,630
but you need to know if someone's done this before

260
00:14:57,650 --> 00:14:58,291
and think about it.

261
00:14:58,911 --> 00:15:01,072
And I knew there had never been a game like Deus Ex.

262
00:15:01,112 --> 00:15:04,554
At least I felt that way in my egotistical world of fantasy.

263
00:15:05,375 --> 00:15:08,037
And I was gonna show everybody that they'd missed the boat.

264
00:15:10,042 --> 00:15:11,343
And then what's the one thing?

265
00:15:12,403 --> 00:15:14,484
We are a very young medium, even today.

266
00:15:14,524 --> 00:15:16,585
I've been saying this for 30 something years

267
00:15:16,645 --> 00:15:18,065
and it's still freaking true.

268
00:15:18,865 --> 00:15:21,667
Anybody who believes that we've had our Citizen Kane,

269
00:15:21,727 --> 00:15:23,747
you know, or whatever, however you want to think about it,

270
00:15:24,067 --> 00:15:25,008
is fooling themselves.

271
00:15:25,128 --> 00:15:28,249
We have not done everything games can and should do.

272
00:15:28,849 --> 00:15:31,190
And you can always find one thing

273
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:32,731
that hasn't been done before.

274
00:15:33,111 --> 00:15:35,152
Even if you're making a My Little Pony game.

275
00:15:35,772 --> 00:15:37,993
You can find, actually, okay, we have some bronies

276
00:15:38,033 --> 00:15:38,833
in the audience, great.

277
00:15:41,114 --> 00:15:43,615
But you can always find one new thing, okay?

278
00:15:45,216 --> 00:15:47,917
And in Deus Ex, I thought the combination of genres

279
00:15:47,937 --> 00:15:50,018
was gonna be unique, it would result in something unique.

280
00:15:50,398 --> 00:15:52,899
And the idea that players could solve problems

281
00:15:52,919 --> 00:15:55,199
the way they wanted to instead of us forcing,

282
00:15:55,420 --> 00:15:56,920
as developers, forcing them to play

283
00:15:56,980 --> 00:15:57,980
the way we wanted them to.

284
00:15:59,141 --> 00:16:01,542
And the plus one, this is really important to me,

285
00:16:01,562 --> 00:16:02,722
it may or may not be important to you,

286
00:16:02,762 --> 00:16:04,063
but do you have something to say?

287
00:16:06,395 --> 00:16:09,078
There has to be something more, in my opinion, in a game

288
00:16:09,118 --> 00:16:12,381
than what's happening just on the surface level of action.

289
00:16:13,302 --> 00:16:14,483
If you don't have something to say,

290
00:16:14,503 --> 00:16:17,405
a theme or an issue you want players to explore,

291
00:16:18,607 --> 00:16:20,448
you are kind of wasting players' time.

292
00:16:21,441 --> 00:16:24,784
and you are wasting your time. I said it. Okay? There you go.

293
00:16:25,985 --> 00:16:28,427
In Deus Ex, I wanted to explore all sorts of big issues, which

294
00:16:28,487 --> 00:16:34,471
I will get to shortly. And I wanted players to explore those

295
00:16:34,531 --> 00:16:37,093
things in ways that only games could allow them to do.

296
00:16:38,656 --> 00:16:40,577
So luckily, where Deus Ex was concerned,

297
00:16:40,897 --> 00:16:42,038
the answers were yes.

298
00:16:42,959 --> 00:16:44,860
So we started in the concept phase.

299
00:16:46,561 --> 00:16:48,962
The first thing that happened was the real world went away

300
00:16:49,043 --> 00:16:53,485
because even in 1997, it was just not possible

301
00:16:53,525 --> 00:16:54,746
to recreate the real world.

302
00:16:54,826 --> 00:16:56,447
So we moved it out to 2052.

303
00:16:56,507 --> 00:16:58,108
That was one of the first decisions we made.

304
00:16:58,649 --> 00:17:00,950
And we had to know what the real world was gonna be like

305
00:17:01,350 --> 00:17:02,211
50 years in the future.

306
00:17:02,991 --> 00:17:04,692
So that led us in a couple of directions.

307
00:17:05,132 --> 00:17:06,852
It led us to cyberpunk fiction,

308
00:17:07,473 --> 00:17:09,913
and it led us to movies like Blade Runner.

309
00:17:10,314 --> 00:17:11,754
But that could only take us so far.

310
00:17:12,574 --> 00:17:17,036
So if we were gonna plug into the real cultural zeitgeist,

311
00:17:18,476 --> 00:17:21,637
we had to pay close attention to things in the real world.

312
00:17:22,598 --> 00:17:24,678
So you didn't have to be a genius, even in 1997,

313
00:17:24,858 --> 00:17:29,180
to see that the news was increasingly filled

314
00:17:29,220 --> 00:17:30,360
with reports of terrorism.

315
00:17:31,519 --> 00:17:35,480
It wasn't a part of our daily lives at that point, but you could kind of see it coming.

316
00:17:37,101 --> 00:17:39,962
If you did a little digging, you started seeing military efforts

317
00:17:40,002 --> 00:17:42,003
to create mechanically augmented soldiers.

318
00:17:42,303 --> 00:17:46,064
And we even found real world cloaking devices.

319
00:17:46,644 --> 00:17:49,945
They're kind of faked and phony, but it was still cool.

320
00:17:49,965 --> 00:17:51,606
We could put it in the game because we found that.

321
00:17:54,310 --> 00:17:56,851
AI research had people talking about the singularity.

322
00:17:56,891 --> 00:17:58,092
They're still talking about that.

323
00:17:58,212 --> 00:17:59,372
I'm still thinking about that.

324
00:17:59,852 --> 00:18:01,353
I'm working on System Shock 3 now.

325
00:18:01,393 --> 00:18:03,614
You'll probably think about it again soon.

326
00:18:05,795 --> 00:18:08,717
But the point where computer AI overtook human intelligence

327
00:18:08,757 --> 00:18:10,498
was on people's minds back then.

328
00:18:11,698 --> 00:18:12,859
And really interesting to us

329
00:18:12,919 --> 00:18:14,620
was the rise of nanotechnology.

330
00:18:16,275 --> 00:18:19,298
So the dangers of that seemed like it'd be fun to explore.

331
00:18:19,799 --> 00:18:21,781
But most important, everywhere you looked in 1997,

332
00:18:22,562 --> 00:18:23,723
there was a conspiracy theory.

333
00:18:24,444 --> 00:18:25,064
It was crazy.

334
00:18:25,345 --> 00:18:29,109
Black helicopters, men in black, manufactured diseases,

335
00:18:29,129 --> 00:18:32,552
you know, sentient AIs, governments serving the needs

336
00:18:32,592 --> 00:18:33,793
of mysterious overlords.

337
00:18:34,114 --> 00:18:35,395
I mean, it was all there, right?

338
00:18:35,735 --> 00:18:36,797
And the World Wide Web, I mean,

339
00:18:36,817 --> 00:18:37,998
who knew where that was going to lead?

340
00:18:39,339 --> 00:18:45,182
People believed in all that stuff. And the world of Deus Ex was being created all around us. We

341
00:18:45,222 --> 00:18:52,287
didn't have to make anything up. It was great. So here are the things I wanted people thinking

342
00:18:52,327 --> 00:18:56,149
about. I created some pillar questions and every decision that we made on the game was

343
00:18:56,229 --> 00:19:00,652
filtered through this mesh. I already mentioned this. So what would happen if you masked up

344
00:19:00,692 --> 00:19:01,252
these genres?

345
00:19:03,347 --> 00:19:05,669
What would happen if you dropped a James Bond guy who

346
00:19:05,709 --> 00:19:08,111
believes in right and wrong and black and white into a world

347
00:19:08,151 --> 00:19:09,392
that's all shades of gray?

348
00:19:12,094 --> 00:19:14,916
What would the world be like if every conspiracy theory people

349
00:19:14,956 --> 00:19:16,838
believe to be true were, in fact, true?

350
00:19:18,539 --> 00:19:20,461
And what did it mean to be human in a world of

351
00:19:21,141 --> 00:19:22,923
augmentation, mechanical and nano?

352
00:19:25,217 --> 00:19:29,498
And finally, how would the world be better off? This was really important. Would the world be

353
00:19:29,539 --> 00:19:35,001
better off as it really is ruled by a secret cabal, of course? Would it be better off if it

354
00:19:35,061 --> 00:19:40,824
was ruled by a sentient AI that connected all of us but cost us our free will? Would it be

355
00:19:40,864 --> 00:19:47,086
better off plunged into a new dark age where free will reigned? Okay. Or would ‑‑

356
00:19:48,862 --> 00:19:50,062
Yeah, anyway, I'll stop there.

357
00:19:50,082 --> 00:19:51,523
I got too much to talk about.

358
00:19:51,784 --> 00:19:53,425
The game would have no bosses to kill.

359
00:19:53,585 --> 00:19:55,486
It was gonna be about the fate of the world

360
00:19:55,646 --> 00:19:57,127
and what you believed it should be.

361
00:19:57,708 --> 00:19:58,989
Now in a novel or a movie,

362
00:19:59,529 --> 00:20:02,991
all you get to do is say, I agree, or I disagree.

363
00:20:03,292 --> 00:20:04,232
You get to interpret.

364
00:20:04,573 --> 00:20:06,894
In a game, I thought, and only in a game,

365
00:20:07,194 --> 00:20:09,196
you could answer those questions for yourself

366
00:20:09,816 --> 00:20:10,897
through your play choices.

367
00:20:11,317 --> 00:20:12,798
That was the power of those questions.

368
00:20:13,849 --> 00:20:16,111
So I also created a set of commandments,

369
00:20:16,151 --> 00:20:18,393
and I encourage you to do this too in your games.

370
00:20:18,413 --> 00:20:20,295
Your teams will appreciate it, I promise you.

371
00:20:21,857 --> 00:20:24,479
These are just the Deus Ex rules of role-playing,

372
00:20:24,519 --> 00:20:25,240
basically, right?

373
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:26,221
Your rules may vary.

374
00:20:27,141 --> 00:20:27,902
Always show the goal.

375
00:20:28,102 --> 00:20:30,905
You should always see what you're trying to accomplish.

376
00:20:30,945 --> 00:20:32,927
It's not fun to try to figure out what you have to do.

377
00:20:32,987 --> 00:20:33,828
It's fun doing it.

378
00:20:35,069 --> 00:20:35,909
You should show the goal.

379
00:20:38,148 --> 00:20:41,850
Problems, not puzzles. It's an obstacle course, not a jigsaw

380
00:20:41,910 --> 00:20:46,292
puzzle. You should never have to read a designer's mind. No

381
00:20:46,372 --> 00:20:49,313
forced failures. Failure is not fun. Getting knocked

382
00:20:49,373 --> 00:20:53,195
unconscious and waking up with a smoking gun in your hand and

383
00:20:53,215 --> 00:20:56,096
dead bodies may make for a great story, but it has nothing to do

384
00:20:56,116 --> 00:20:58,977
with games. Situations where the player has no chance to react in

385
00:20:59,037 --> 00:21:00,678
the Deus Ex world are bad.

386
00:21:09,382 --> 00:21:13,425
I already said this. It's about playing a role, not about rolling dice. We have better

387
00:21:13,485 --> 00:21:19,229
simulation tools and techniques than Gary Gygax and Dave Arneson had back in the 70s. Why do

388
00:21:19,249 --> 00:21:25,353
we still have character classes and skill levels and die rolls? So we were going to try to do

389
00:21:25,393 --> 00:21:31,918
away with that stuff. If something is cool, don't even think about letting an NPC do it.

390
00:21:32,398 --> 00:21:36,321
Players do the cool stuff. NPCs watch the player do the cool stuff.

391
00:21:38,459 --> 00:21:41,682
You want constant rewards to drive players onward.

392
00:21:41,802 --> 00:21:43,623
You have to reward players regularly.

393
00:21:46,786 --> 00:21:48,367
This is genius right here.

394
00:21:48,828 --> 00:21:51,710
As the player gets better, make the game harder.

395
00:21:54,653 --> 00:21:55,574
Think 3D.

396
00:21:55,754 --> 00:21:59,497
I believe that 3D maps can't be laid out on graph paper.

397
00:21:59,737 --> 00:22:01,359
You're more than welcome to disagree with me.

398
00:22:01,739 --> 00:22:04,101
But if players aren't looking up and down constantly,

399
00:22:04,862 --> 00:22:06,063
you might as well make a 2D game.

400
00:22:08,508 --> 00:22:09,329
And be connected.

401
00:22:09,769 --> 00:22:12,010
Tunnels that go from A to B are not very

