00:26:28,918 --> 00:26:30,500
And if people compare our role-playing elements

486
00:26:30,540 --> 00:26:31,981
to Baldur's Gate, we're dead.

487
00:26:33,542 --> 00:26:35,203
There was just no telling how it was going to go.

488
00:26:35,604 --> 00:26:37,144
But there was also nothing anybody could do.

489
00:26:37,245 --> 00:26:40,486
We shipped the game, and we'd soon know how people responded.

490
00:26:40,526 --> 00:26:42,868
And I'll try to get to that here today.

491
00:26:43,628 --> 00:26:46,470
So let me kind of rip through what we did right and wrong.

492
00:26:48,271 --> 00:26:50,472
It's ironic, because we made a game where there was no right

493
00:26:50,512 --> 00:26:52,854
and wrong, and yet plenty went right and wrong in the

494
00:26:52,894 --> 00:26:53,714
development, I'll tell you.

495
00:26:55,020 --> 00:26:59,925
So what went right? We had a clear high-level vision. I've already talked a little bit about that.

496
00:27:00,626 --> 00:27:03,949
We knew what game we wanted to make, or at least what kind of game we wanted to make.

497
00:27:04,710 --> 00:27:09,334
It was a natural outgrowth of games from companies like this.

498
00:27:10,415 --> 00:27:12,457
We built on a foundation that already existed.

499
00:27:14,530 --> 00:27:16,551
As you know, it was a game I had been thinking about for

500
00:27:16,591 --> 00:27:17,211
many years.

501
00:27:17,511 --> 00:27:18,992
So it didn't come out of nowhere.

502
00:27:20,072 --> 00:27:21,973
We had a good idea of what game we wanted to make.

503
00:27:22,553 --> 00:27:24,654
So the lesson here is if there's a game that you have

504
00:27:24,694 --> 00:27:25,875
to make, never give up.

505
00:27:25,935 --> 00:27:27,876
Because someone's going to be stupid enough to give you the

506
00:27:27,916 --> 00:27:28,536
money someday.

507
00:27:31,767 --> 00:27:37,508
We had very clear goals. Those commandments, they were a great start. But we had to move from

508
00:27:37,648 --> 00:27:42,369
abstract ideas to game design specifics. We had to start thinking about what players wanted to

509
00:27:42,429 --> 00:27:48,891
do and not what we wanted to do. So what were our goals? We wanted players thinking about who

510
00:27:48,971 --> 00:27:54,972
they were in the world. Character differentiation, totally important. We wanted players to

511
00:27:54,992 --> 00:27:56,653
think how they wanted to behave in the world.

512
00:27:57,915 --> 00:28:02,639
We had to wean players from traditional games, puzzle games and fighting games to games where

513
00:28:02,659 --> 00:28:10,006
they actually had to, I don't know what's the word, think. God, I have an attitude. We wanted a

514
00:28:10,046 --> 00:28:16,512
game that tuned itself to each player's play style. Rather than forcing players to play the

515
00:28:16,552 --> 00:28:17,733
way we wanted them to play.

516
00:28:18,878 --> 00:28:22,321
We wanted them to feel like they were actually in the world.

517
00:28:22,381 --> 00:28:24,483
They needed to be able to apply real world logic

518
00:28:24,503 --> 00:28:25,664
to the problems in the game.

519
00:28:26,465 --> 00:28:27,966
And everything in the game had to be based

520
00:28:28,006 --> 00:28:28,687
on something real.

521
00:28:28,767 --> 00:28:32,030
I'm sure if there's anybody who worked on Deus Ex

522
00:28:32,090 --> 00:28:34,452
in this audience, I'm sure you hate me

523
00:28:34,693 --> 00:28:38,196
because I made everybody base stuff on real stuff.

524
00:28:39,517 --> 00:28:41,839
And could we put players in control of the experience?

525
00:28:42,079 --> 00:28:44,401
If not, Deus Ex was gonna be a failed experiment.

526
00:28:46,192 --> 00:28:50,054
The third thing that went right, we didn't skimp on pre-production. I said we had six months.

527
00:28:50,414 --> 00:28:57,157
You can always use more, okay? But we did okay. We started out with that team of six figuring

528
00:28:57,237 --> 00:29:04,081
out what game we wanted to make. We started working out our missions, way too many of them.

529
00:29:05,101 --> 00:29:08,783
I'll come back to this in a minute. We hammered on our game systems.

530
00:29:11,002 --> 00:29:12,263
But here's the thing.

531
00:29:12,423 --> 00:29:14,124
I have two number threes.

532
00:29:14,144 --> 00:29:14,564
Look at that.

533
00:29:16,806 --> 00:29:18,347
I needed more pre-production on this deck.

534
00:29:20,389 --> 00:29:23,371
By March of 1998, we thought we knew everything we needed to

535
00:29:23,391 --> 00:29:25,533
know to make a game, but man, were we wrong.

536
00:29:26,593 --> 00:29:27,794
We were open to change.

537
00:29:28,034 --> 00:29:28,815
Be open to change.

538
00:29:28,875 --> 00:29:31,177
Anybody who tells you that when you get to the end of

