00:29:34,099 --> 00:29:35,280
never made a game, right?

541
00:29:35,300 --> 00:29:37,021
And it's usually going to be someone wearing a suit.

542
00:29:37,121 --> 00:29:38,062
Don't let them get away with it.

543
00:29:40,084 --> 00:29:41,127
So why did things change?

544
00:29:41,528 --> 00:29:43,072
Well, we had new people join the team.

545
00:29:43,132 --> 00:29:44,195
They had new ideas.

546
00:29:45,801 --> 00:29:47,042
as we brought on new people,

547
00:29:47,362 --> 00:29:50,524
we found ourselves with a team of hardcore shooter players,

548
00:29:50,684 --> 00:29:53,747
Ultima fans, RTS players, I mean, it was crazy.

549
00:29:55,388 --> 00:29:57,529
And it was my job and my lead's team's job

550
00:29:57,849 --> 00:30:01,912
to kind of manage that, the conflicts that raged

551
00:30:02,072 --> 00:30:03,273
over the kinds of games

552
00:30:03,313 --> 00:30:04,854
that all those new people wanted to make.

553
00:30:05,355 --> 00:30:06,675
By the way, if whoever made this diagram

554
00:30:06,695 --> 00:30:08,157
is in the audience, I'm sorry, I stole it.

555
00:30:10,296 --> 00:30:14,543
Our game systems didn't work as well in reality as we

556
00:30:14,563 --> 00:30:16,426
thought they would on paper, or as I thought

557
00:30:16,446 --> 00:30:17,147
they would on paper.

558
00:30:19,213 --> 00:30:22,756
Another thing we did right was we always had a playable build.

559
00:30:23,196 --> 00:30:25,198
Again, this is like common practice now.

560
00:30:26,358 --> 00:30:28,860
We always knew where we were, even if that was painful.

561
00:30:30,301 --> 00:30:33,823
Proto missions, critical to all of our scheduling and the

562
00:30:33,843 --> 00:30:34,884
quality of the final game.

563
00:30:36,105 --> 00:30:39,387
The first one we built was a White House mission, which we

