00:31:03,041 --> 00:31:05,042
this is when I got the first inkling

576
00:31:05,062 --> 00:31:07,063
that it wasn't actually going to be any fun.

577
00:31:07,844 --> 00:31:10,405
I was too stubborn to cut it at that point or change it,

578
00:31:10,505 --> 00:31:12,266
but we got a sense that AI

579
00:31:12,306 --> 00:31:13,847
was gonna be a big challenge for us.

580
00:31:15,893 --> 00:31:19,876
And then shortly after that, actually it was almost a year

581
00:31:19,976 --> 00:31:22,938
after that, we had some real missions built.

582
00:31:23,198 --> 00:31:25,980
And we let real people play the game.

583
00:31:26,080 --> 00:31:28,381
You could do everything you were going to do in the game.

584
00:31:28,421 --> 00:31:29,642
And it really wasn't hacked.

585
00:31:30,183 --> 00:31:32,244
It was as documented, but not hacked.

586
00:31:33,325 --> 00:31:35,166
And we let real people come in and play the game.

587
00:31:35,226 --> 00:31:36,947
Do not tell your publisher you're doing this.

588
00:31:39,757 --> 00:31:43,001
We needed the opinions of people who understood our kind

589
00:31:43,021 --> 00:31:46,505
of game and the development process better than we did.

590
00:31:46,966 --> 00:31:48,748
So we had real people come in and play the game.

591
00:31:49,529 --> 00:31:51,671
And listening to their responses, I called that

592
00:31:51,771 --> 00:31:54,895
particular milestone the wow, these missions suck milestone.

593
00:31:56,803 --> 00:32:03,348
We had a lot of work to do. We had potential. Everybody saw that. But we had a lot of work to

594
00:32:03,388 --> 00:32:09,613
do. So we ended up cutting and cutting and cutting. We had too much game. Harvey Smith, the

595
00:32:09,633 --> 00:32:17,259
lead designer, had been telling me stop being a kitchen sink designer and cut stuff. And I'll

596
00:32:17,299 --> 00:32:20,582
come back to that, too. We licensed tech. That was something we did right. We used Unreal

597
00:32:20,602 --> 00:32:23,804
to make a tournament. And for the most part, it worked out really well.

598
00:32:25,797 --> 00:32:28,438
Adding what we needed was much easier than it could have been.

599
00:32:29,398 --> 00:32:30,959
Unreal Ed was really powerful,

600
00:32:30,979 --> 00:32:32,780
superior to anything else at the time.

601
00:32:33,460 --> 00:32:35,261
Unreal Script allowed programmers to do lots

602
00:32:35,281 --> 00:32:37,062
of interesting things easily and quickly.

603
00:32:38,823 --> 00:32:42,284
That's my entire programming team, plus one of the testers.

604
00:32:43,725 --> 00:32:45,386
Three programmers made Deus Ex.

605
00:32:45,766 --> 00:32:46,767
They were very overworked.

606
00:32:48,028 --> 00:32:50,130
but they were able to do it because we licensed stuff.

607
00:32:50,791 --> 00:32:51,912
So what went wrong?

608
00:32:52,533 --> 00:32:53,253
All sorts of stuff.

609
00:32:53,654 --> 00:32:55,576
Team structure did not work.

610
00:32:55,596 --> 00:33:01,682
I had two people qualified to be lead designers,

611
00:33:01,722 --> 00:33:02,763
so instead of picking one,

612
00:33:02,803 --> 00:33:04,225
I said you're both lead designers,

613
00:33:04,505 --> 00:33:06,367
I'm gonna give you both your own design team.

614
00:33:08,029 --> 00:33:08,670
Don't do that.

615
00:33:08,730 --> 00:33:09,911
I thought I could manage the tension

616
00:33:09,951 --> 00:33:12,334
between the immersive sim guys and the Ultima guys.

617
00:33:13,655 --> 00:33:15,337
And what ended up happening was that

618
00:33:16,038 --> 00:33:18,601
I had to call one of the design teams one

619
00:33:18,781 --> 00:33:22,145
and the other one A, because neither would be B or two.

620
00:33:25,629 --> 00:33:26,750
Yeah, yeah.

621
00:33:28,005 --> 00:33:35,707
So, eventually I had to just say one of you is the lead designer, a couple people left, it was very sad, but it was the right thing for the game.

622
00:33:36,727 --> 00:33:44,588
On the art side, we also had problems because the artists at first, for about the first year of the project, actually reported to a guy in Dallas, not to me.

623
00:33:45,388 --> 00:33:51,469
And I argued and screamed about matrix management not working, and ultimately I won and the artists ended up reporting to me.

624
00:33:51,489 --> 00:33:57,130
And I can only imagine what the game might have looked like if the artists had reported to me from the start. That would have been interesting.

625
00:33:58,117 --> 00:34:02,881
One of the things I probably should have talked about that I did right was I had the right

626
00:34:02,961 --> 00:34:03,461
leads team.

627
00:34:03,501 --> 00:34:07,765
That's Chris Norton in the middle, Harvey Smith on the left, and Jay Lee on the right.

628
00:34:08,245 --> 00:34:12,668
Lead designer, lead programmer and assistant director, and art director.

629
00:34:13,009 --> 00:34:18,113
Those guys do not get enough credit for the creative aspects of the game, the fact that

630
00:34:18,133 --> 00:34:20,355
we shipped it all, and managing the team.

631
00:34:20,435 --> 00:34:23,097
So give those guys their due.

632
00:34:27,982 --> 00:34:29,163
Yeah, people think I make games,

633
00:34:29,183 --> 00:34:31,164
they like pour out of my forehead, you know,

634
00:34:31,385 --> 00:34:33,707
like, I don't know, like I bang my head on a desk

635
00:34:33,767 --> 00:34:35,969
and blood pours out or something.

636
00:34:36,509 --> 00:34:39,532
So the lesson learned here, have a great leads group

637
00:34:40,853 --> 00:34:43,475
and don't underestimate the importance of team dynamics.

638
00:34:44,660 --> 00:34:48,543
Okay. Another thing that went wrong was our goals were too

639
00:34:48,583 --> 00:34:51,044
big. We weren't realistic. If you're going to advance the

640
00:34:51,084 --> 00:34:54,286
state of the art, and I hope you all try to do that, you have to

641
00:34:54,326 --> 00:34:58,148
think big. But you really don't want to create missions, which I

642
00:34:58,248 --> 00:35:01,270
did, by the way. I have to take responsibility for. You're going

643
00:35:01,310 --> 00:35:05,452
to liberate 2,000 people from a concentration camp in the

644
00:35:05,492 --> 00:35:06,993
Midwest. Don't do that.

645
00:35:07,473 --> 00:35:14,837
Okay, there's going to be a full-on war between the Russo-Mexican alliance and the United States government in Austin, Texas

646
00:35:15,477 --> 00:35:17,018
Don't do that. Okay

647
00:35:18,538 --> 00:35:23,341
Harvey Smith and another designer Steve Powers came to me one day and said you cannot make this game

648
00:35:24,201 --> 00:35:31,263
We cannot tell this story and they browbeat me until I gave in and we cut a bunch and the game was better for it.

649
00:35:31,743 --> 00:35:36,985
So define your creative box, define it by the limit according to the limitations of your tech

650
00:35:37,785 --> 00:35:40,186
and also by the limitations of what's right for your game.

651
00:35:40,466 --> 00:35:45,368
Okay, the job of the creative director, the game director on the game is to define the

