726
00:39:32,527 --> 00:39:33,647
So how did people respond?

727
00:39:33,667 --> 00:39:34,788
I said I was gonna get back to that.

728
00:39:35,088 --> 00:39:36,768
Did we get killed or did we rule the world?

729
00:39:38,857 --> 00:39:39,617
Well, we didn't die.

730
00:39:40,198 --> 00:39:41,198
So that tells you something.

731
00:39:41,298 --> 00:39:43,498
And we reviewed really well and won a bunch of awards

732
00:39:43,538 --> 00:39:43,998
and all that.

733
00:39:45,539 --> 00:39:47,939
But we were surprised by a lot of what players did.

734
00:39:49,719 --> 00:39:52,280
Even seasoned gamers were paralyzed by choice.

735
00:39:52,580 --> 00:39:53,200
It was strange.

736
00:39:53,540 --> 00:39:56,281
When they would get to a choice point early on

737
00:39:56,301 --> 00:40:00,481
in our testing, and I would see gamers push the keyboard

738
00:40:00,521 --> 00:40:04,182
away and like go, wait, I have to make a real choice?

739
00:40:04,882 --> 00:40:06,823
Games had trained people not to think.

740
00:40:06,883 --> 00:40:08,143
It was unbelievable to me.

741
00:40:10,500 --> 00:40:14,062
And what I expected was that players were going to find a play style.

742
00:40:14,082 --> 00:40:16,064
They were going to say, I like fighting or I like sneaking.

743
00:40:16,084 --> 00:40:17,184
And they just play that way.

744
00:40:17,585 --> 00:40:18,966
But that's not what happened.

745
00:40:19,286 --> 00:40:23,769
What happened instead was players would get to a choice point, save the game, try something,

746
00:40:24,449 --> 00:40:27,491
go back to the save game, try something different, go back to the save game,

747
00:40:27,511 --> 00:40:30,373
try something different, and then pick the one they liked the best.

748
00:40:31,394 --> 00:40:37,397
It was very frustrating, but then you know once people buy your game. It's their game, so you can't be too upset about that

749
00:40:38,738 --> 00:40:44,741
But we did discover that players could interact with our simulation as shallow as it was in a lot of ways and do things that

750
00:40:44,801 --> 00:40:45,642
We didn't expect

751
00:40:47,423 --> 00:40:49,544
Everybody knows the lamb ladder story, right?

752
00:40:49,664 --> 00:40:56,388
I mean people would take a light attack munition put it on a wall jump on it put another one higher up jump on it

753
00:40:56,468 --> 00:40:58,409
Put another one higher up jump on it and

754
00:40:59,490 --> 00:41:01,733
they could get out of the world.

755
00:41:02,794 --> 00:41:05,237
So if you go do this in Deus Ex,

756
00:41:05,277 --> 00:41:07,460
on a lot of maps you'll find ladders

757
00:41:07,881 --> 00:41:09,843
and crates outside of the map,

758
00:41:10,444 --> 00:41:11,906
so you can actually stack them up

759
00:41:11,946 --> 00:41:13,027
and get back in the game world.

760
00:41:15,526 --> 00:41:19,629
Yeah. There was a time about a year after we shipped, I saw

761
00:41:19,689 --> 00:41:23,751
somebody in a place I had played myself a hundred times and

762
00:41:23,932 --> 00:41:28,995
watched people play a thousand times, and there was a guard

763
00:41:29,055 --> 00:41:31,876
standing there in front of an open doorway with laser

764
00:41:31,936 --> 00:41:35,439
triggers that would set off an alarm and two guys on patrols

765
00:41:35,479 --> 00:41:39,141
on the other side of the door. It was three problems, okay? And

766
00:41:39,181 --> 00:41:42,223
I watched this one guy sneaking around, moving explosive

767
00:41:42,243 --> 00:41:43,123
barrels around.

768
00:41:43,724 --> 00:41:47,134
He took one shot with the pistol and solved all three problems at once.

769
00:41:48,277 --> 00:41:49,701
And I fell on the floor.

770
00:41:50,960 --> 00:41:53,182
And I guarantee you, no one else in the world

771
00:41:53,222 --> 00:41:55,364
had ever done that before.

772
00:41:55,764 --> 00:41:56,444
That was cool.

773
00:41:57,105 --> 00:41:59,307
Seeing people actually doing things that were not

774
00:41:59,387 --> 00:42:02,550
anticipated was cool and was one of our measures of success.

775
00:42:02,790 --> 00:42:05,472
By the way, know how you are going to define success

776
00:42:05,512 --> 00:42:06,493
in any game you make.

777
00:42:06,553 --> 00:42:08,575
If you can't define success, you are not

778
00:42:08,675 --> 00:42:10,516
ready to make that game.

779
00:42:11,017 --> 00:42:13,739
So conversation was my definition of success.

780
00:42:18,448 --> 00:42:21,030
wasn't it cool I would hear someone say when you rescued

781
00:42:21,050 --> 00:42:23,732
that prisoner from the cells under UNATCO headquarters and

782
00:42:23,772 --> 00:42:28,936
someone else would say what cells? That was a win. I used to

783
00:42:28,976 --> 00:42:32,339
say all the time I love the pistol and the team wanted to

784
00:42:32,379 --> 00:42:34,600
cut the pistol because it was the weakest weapon in the game.

785
00:42:34,700 --> 00:42:37,222
It's like, no, don't cut the pistol. I love it. It makes me

786
00:42:37,422 --> 00:42:39,024
think. It's my favorite weapon.

787
00:42:40,415 --> 00:42:44,719
There was another time, I was at an event like this, actually,

788
00:42:44,999 --> 00:42:47,442
and after the talk, I went out, I never do this, I went out for

789
00:42:47,502 --> 00:42:50,044
drinks with some people in the audience, do not ask me, I won't

790
00:42:50,084 --> 00:42:50,284
do it.

791
00:42:50,923 --> 00:42:55,705
But an inebriated fan sat down next to me and said,

792
00:42:55,745 --> 00:42:58,446
how can you make that right wing piece of trash?

793
00:42:59,026 --> 00:43:00,286
And before I could answer,

794
00:43:00,487 --> 00:43:01,687
I don't do a good drunk imitation.

795
00:43:02,207 --> 00:43:05,909
And then another drunk fan sat down on the other side

796
00:43:05,949 --> 00:43:07,969
and said, what do you mean right wing piece of trash?

797
00:43:08,009 --> 00:43:10,010
It was left wing propaganda from the start.

798
00:43:10,810 --> 00:43:13,351
And the cool thing was they were both right, okay.

799
00:43:14,272 --> 00:43:15,612
Based on how they had played the game

800
00:43:15,632 --> 00:43:17,493
and the end games that they had selected and everything.

801
00:43:17,713 --> 00:43:19,554
And I just got up and left them to argue.

802
00:43:19,694 --> 00:43:20,234
It was awesome.

803
00:43:22,758 --> 00:43:25,460
So instead of talking about how they killed the final boss or

804
00:43:25,500 --> 00:43:29,142
saved the princess, they talked about the fate of the world.

805
00:43:29,363 --> 00:43:32,865
That was success. That was exactly what I wanted them

806
00:43:32,905 --> 00:43:38,228
doing. So that was what Deus Ex was all about. It wasn't about

807
00:43:38,808 --> 00:43:40,750
what the development team thought the world should be. It

808
00:43:40,790 --> 00:43:44,872
was about what you, not your avatar, not the character, what

809
00:43:44,912 --> 00:43:46,013
you thought the world should be.

810
00:43:48,227 --> 00:43:52,332
So, like Bruce Sterling and every other D&D dungeon master,

811
00:43:52,432 --> 00:43:54,614
we provided the skeleton of the experience.

812
00:43:55,315 --> 00:43:58,399
And players put the meat on the bones, okay?

813
00:43:58,739 --> 00:44:01,122
There was one guy, okay, I was at GDC,

814
00:44:01,342 --> 00:44:02,644
this was several years ago,

815
00:44:03,605 --> 00:44:06,168
and a guy came up to me dressed as JC Denton.

816
00:44:06,908 --> 00:44:12,913
okay? And he was German and I will not try and do a German accent, but he said, I've played

817
00:44:12,933 --> 00:44:19,638
through Deus Ex 63 times and had a different experience every time. And I pushed him on it and

818
00:44:19,658 --> 00:44:24,662
I said, it's not bad. And he said, no, I've played through it 63 times. And then he said words

819
00:44:24,702 --> 00:44:30,926
that were magic to my ears. I am going back to Germany after this show. And I was grateful

820
00:44:30,966 --> 00:44:33,688
because I really don't want to be on the same continent with that guy.

821
00:44:37,894 --> 00:44:42,796
So in the end, Deus Ex was, as all cyberpunk fiction is,

822
00:44:43,617 --> 00:44:45,778
about you and me and the future as it might be.

823
00:44:46,558 --> 00:44:48,959
No aliens, no teleporters, no demons.

824
00:44:49,780 --> 00:44:51,661
Just people and politics and business

825
00:44:52,021 --> 00:44:53,922
and stuff that's usually beyond our control.

826
00:44:54,725 --> 00:44:57,687
But in the game world, you could actually make a difference

827
00:44:57,747 --> 00:44:59,347
and remake the world in your image.

828
00:44:59,447 --> 00:45:00,908
That was what Deus Ex was about.

829
00:45:00,948 --> 00:45:02,869
It was a powerful idea, at least to me,

830
00:45:03,349 --> 00:45:05,570
and I think it's at least in part responsible

831
00:45:05,610 --> 00:45:07,231
for the fact that all of you are here today.

832
00:45:08,971 --> 00:45:12,773
So that's the really quick version of a very long talk.

833
00:45:13,953 --> 00:45:16,194
But here's my final thought for all of you.

834
00:45:16,675 --> 00:45:18,535
I sincerely hope that every one of you

835
00:45:18,575 --> 00:45:20,196
gets an opportunity to work on the game

836
00:45:20,236 --> 00:45:22,237
of your dreams someday, okay?

837
00:45:22,797 --> 00:45:24,038
It's amazing.

838
00:45:25,519 --> 00:45:31,724
And I also hope that every one of you gets to work on something that is still relevant 17 years after you make it.

839
00:45:32,144 --> 00:45:35,326
And that has a life of its own beyond you.

840
00:45:35,407 --> 00:45:38,809
People ask me all the time how I feel about the new Deus Ex games.

841
00:45:39,129 --> 00:45:41,571
And all I can tell them is, it's amazing.

842
00:45:42,412 --> 00:45:46,235
It's amazing because it has a life beyond me, it has a life beyond my team.

843
00:45:48,237 --> 00:45:50,318
It's bigger than we were.

844
00:45:50,518 --> 00:45:52,980
And I get to play Deus Ex games where I don't know all the secrets.

845
00:45:54,092 --> 00:45:55,052
So thanks for listening.

846
00:45:55,353 --> 00:45:56,333
That's what I got.

847
00:46:03,318 --> 00:46:06,541
And thanks to the GDC folks for letting me go eight minutes

848
00:46:06,661 --> 00:46:09,083
over, fill out your questionnaires or whatever

849
00:46:09,123 --> 00:46:11,204
those things are online.

850
00:46:11,845 --> 00:46:14,406
And if you have questions or something, we ran out of time.

851
00:46:15,547 --> 00:46:18,850
And I can stay out in the hallway or go somewhere if you

852
00:46:18,870 --> 00:46:20,091
want to ask some questions for a little while.

853
00:46:22,672 --> 00:46:23,013
What's that?

854
00:46:24,754 --> 00:46:37,423
I can't hear you. I'm sorry. What time is it? Dude, why did I rush through this? I totally rushed

855
00:46:37,463 --> 00:46:43,547
through the last half of this thing. Okay. Any questions?

856
00:46:52,685 --> 00:46:54,366
No question? Oh wait, we have a question.

857
00:46:54,446 --> 00:46:56,447
Say your name and who you are.

858
00:46:56,607 --> 00:46:57,967
My name is Mitchell Sabag,

859
00:46:58,307 --> 00:47:02,049
and I recently presented a post-audit narrative summit

860
00:47:02,169 --> 00:47:03,390
on Thief the Dark Project.

861
00:47:03,910 --> 00:47:06,211
So I found that talk of yours

862
00:47:06,251 --> 00:47:09,033
to be incredibly insightful and affection.

863
00:47:09,673 --> 00:47:15,876
Now, with regards to how you were faced with limitations

864
00:47:15,936 --> 00:47:17,397
with regards to your design,

865
00:47:17,837 --> 00:47:19,938
and how you had to essentially craft your game

866
00:47:19,978 --> 00:47:20,958
through subtraction.

867
00:47:22,240 --> 00:47:32,127
How did you approach designing these small maps around the various player personalities

868
00:47:32,187 --> 00:47:35,629
like explorers, adventurers, killers, etc.?

869
00:47:36,250 --> 00:47:42,834
And how did this come about given the limitations and coordination between the various teams?

870
00:47:45,419 --> 00:47:47,080
Realistically, like I said, there was a lot of smoke

871
00:47:47,120 --> 00:47:49,041
and mirrors going on in Deus Ex.

872
00:47:49,101 --> 00:47:52,343
We, like I said, our simulation was just deep enough

873
00:47:52,363 --> 00:47:55,565
that players to this day actually still find solutions

874
00:47:55,585 --> 00:47:56,965
to problems that we didn't plan.

875
00:47:57,606 --> 00:48:00,768
But the team, the design team,

876
00:48:00,828 --> 00:48:03,749
and I feel bad for those guys even now

877
00:48:03,849 --> 00:48:09,192
because every map had, or every problem and challenge had

878
00:48:09,761 --> 00:48:12,663
a sneaky path and a combat path

879
00:48:13,284 --> 00:48:17,887
and a sort of a character interaction path.

880
00:48:18,787 --> 00:48:22,690
So that was, we had to make sure that there was a way

881
00:48:22,710 --> 00:48:24,571
to play through it for every play style.

882
00:48:24,952 --> 00:48:27,673
And then we counted on players finding other solutions

883
00:48:27,753 --> 00:48:29,034
beyond that, okay?

884
00:48:29,054 --> 00:48:31,876
I'm not sure if that answered your question,

885
00:48:31,976 --> 00:48:36,239
but that was, we just pre-planned some paths

886
00:48:36,299 --> 00:48:36,820
through the game.

887
00:48:38,080 --> 00:48:40,881
No, I think that perfectly explains it.

888
00:48:41,681 --> 00:48:42,521
Thank you very much.

889
00:48:42,661 --> 00:48:43,522
You are very welcome.

890
00:48:46,343 --> 00:48:48,483
Hi, oh wait, let me go over to the other side.

891
00:48:48,744 --> 00:48:50,184
Okay, name and who you are.

892
00:48:50,604 --> 00:48:52,025
Hi, my name's Amir Rajan.

893
00:48:52,545 --> 00:48:54,666
I'm actually an indie game developer.

894
00:48:54,706 --> 00:48:56,686
I'm lucky enough to be able to do this full time.

895
00:48:57,559 --> 00:49:04,341
And you mentioned that your games need to have some sort of message or you want to say something through your games.

896
00:49:05,261 --> 00:49:12,284
Could you expand on that a little bit, primarily from the perspective of maybe a large swath of genres of games,

897
00:49:12,324 --> 00:49:16,805
some of them are super casual versus mid-core versus very hardcore games?

898
00:49:18,717 --> 00:49:22,418
what does it mean to say something when it's not full of narrative?

899
00:49:22,558 --> 00:49:27,380
Yeah, okay. I think I perhaps overstated to make my point.

900
00:49:27,420 --> 00:49:27,640
I mean...

901
00:49:27,680 --> 00:49:28,720
Oh, I agree with you, don't worry.

902
00:49:28,880 --> 00:49:34,322
I'm obsessing right now about a game called, you know, 100 with an exclamation point after it.

903
00:49:35,742 --> 00:49:37,583
It doesn't need a message, okay?

904
00:49:37,723 --> 00:49:44,685
But a game that has a narrative or even one that has...

905
00:49:45,870 --> 00:49:47,290
I'm trying not to name names.

906
00:49:47,610 --> 00:49:48,210
Name them.

907
00:49:48,570 --> 00:49:49,650
It's so tempting.

908
00:49:51,251 --> 00:49:57,952
But any game that has any kind of narrative, however deep, can actually ask players to think about something.

909
00:49:59,472 --> 00:50:06,433
In Epic Mickey, for example, I doubt anybody even knows this, at least consciously,

910
00:50:06,493 --> 00:50:09,434
but for me the game was about how important are family and friends to you.

911
00:50:10,714 --> 00:50:13,555
Not family and friends are important in a movie or a book.

912
00:50:15,127 --> 00:50:17,949
the theme, which you don't want players thinking,

913
00:50:17,969 --> 00:50:19,751
or I mean readers thinking about your theme,

914
00:50:19,771 --> 00:50:22,713
you want them kind of ingesting it subconsciously.

915
00:50:23,353 --> 00:50:24,834
And in a game, it's kind of the same thing.

916
00:50:24,894 --> 00:50:26,495
You want them ingesting it subconsciously.

917
00:50:27,036 --> 00:50:29,878
But games ask questions.

918
00:50:30,858 --> 00:50:35,682
Movies and books and opera, they make statements.

919
00:50:36,362 --> 00:50:38,403
Family and friends are important is very different

920
00:50:38,503 --> 00:50:41,345
than how important are family and friends to you.

921
00:50:43,347 --> 00:50:51,220
and is it better to be more powerful and alone or less powerful with friends who will help you?

922
00:50:51,902 --> 00:50:54,346
What does it mean to be forgotten and rejected?

923
00:50:55,054 --> 00:50:55,915
How does that feel?

924
00:50:57,075 --> 00:50:59,657
So even a Mickey Mouse game can ask questions like that.

925
00:50:59,917 --> 00:51:01,838
And if you think about it in terms of questions,

926
00:51:02,739 --> 00:51:05,601
and then create game systems and gameplay

927
00:51:05,641 --> 00:51:07,662
that allow players to explore those questions

928
00:51:08,063 --> 00:51:10,684
in subtle, subconscious ways,

929
00:51:11,785 --> 00:51:13,786
I think games can actually be

930
00:51:14,667 --> 00:51:16,528
an even more remarkable medium than we are.

931
00:51:16,548 --> 00:51:18,049
Thank you.

932
00:51:18,589 --> 00:51:19,650
Yeah.

933
00:51:19,670 --> 00:51:20,491
Hi, my name's Pete.

934
00:51:21,151 --> 00:51:22,652
My voice is a little broken because GDC.

935
00:51:24,604 --> 00:51:28,946
So one question, I have a two-part question. The first part is something that's bothered me for 17 years.

936
00:51:29,326 --> 00:51:29,846
Oh God.

937
00:51:30,207 --> 00:51:31,927
What does JC stand for?

938
00:51:34,048 --> 00:51:35,189
It stands for Jesus Christ.

939
00:51:35,809 --> 00:51:37,670
It does stand for Jesus Christ, okay.

940
00:51:37,690 --> 00:51:41,631
Yeah, but there's more to the story than that. Hold on.

941
00:51:41,852 --> 00:51:42,152
Okay.

942
00:51:42,992 --> 00:51:46,794
One of my best friends is a wonderful writer named Bradley Denton, who you should all go read.

943
00:51:46,814 --> 00:51:49,095
He wrote a book called Blackburn, which you should all read.

944
00:51:49,976 --> 00:51:53,101
And if you want to know about me and my friends, he wrote a book called Lunatics, which you

945
00:51:53,121 --> 00:51:54,824
should all read, and then you can try and guess who I am.

946
00:51:56,467 --> 00:51:57,529
Anyway, he is...

947
00:51:59,448 --> 00:52:01,329
one of the nicest humans on the planet.

948
00:52:02,230 --> 00:52:04,931
And I call him helpful guy,

949
00:52:05,011 --> 00:52:06,892
because if you ever need any help with anything,

950
00:52:06,952 --> 00:52:08,093
he is there for you.

951
00:52:08,854 --> 00:52:11,335
And he's so helpful, it gets annoying sometimes.

952
00:52:11,875 --> 00:52:14,757
So back then I would often find myself saying,

953
00:52:14,917 --> 00:52:16,378
Jesus Christ, Denton.

954
00:52:17,819 --> 00:52:20,501
Jesus Christ, Denton, don't be so helpful.

955
00:52:21,121 --> 00:52:23,403
And so when it came time to name the character,

956
00:52:23,443 --> 00:52:24,323
it was JC Denton.

957
00:52:25,164 --> 00:52:25,824
That's interesting.

958
00:52:31,734 --> 00:52:33,775
So, I had a two part question actually, if you don't mind.

959
00:52:33,895 --> 00:52:35,055
Okay, we'll make it quick.

960
00:52:35,616 --> 00:52:42,058
Obviously, the internet went crazy over this sort of conspiracy theory that it was Jesus Christ because of what he represented.

961
00:52:42,158 --> 00:52:44,359
And obviously no one knew that story, I guess.

962
00:52:45,840 --> 00:52:47,540
I'm not sure I ever told that story.

963
00:52:49,421 --> 00:52:51,402
Did you find that a lot of people came out of the woodwork?

964
00:52:51,422 --> 00:52:57,504
Because it's a conspiracy theory centric game, what was the craziest conspiracy theory around the game development that you've ever heard?

965
00:52:58,344 --> 00:52:59,085
Ah, wow.

966
00:53:00,202 --> 00:53:02,547
I'm not actually sure. I don't have an answer for that.

967
00:53:02,847 --> 00:53:07,115
Sorry. It was a complicated question. Thank you.

